<p>The hours were from 8 to 10 pm,   2 to 4 am,  8 to 10 am, and 2 to 4 pm.  From 2 to 4 last night was wet and stormy and I spent the time in bed in the guard house, as also did the guards on the other posts.<br/>All men on the "Shropshire" were paid this morning from 10 to 11. I was paid &pound;2.5.0.<br/>[Shorthand transcribed as follows]  I wrote to Tom Douglas today.  [end of shorthand]<br/>I was in Weymouth this evening and had tea with private Perks who is living in Weymouth. Then we went to the Pavilion Theatre to see a new play Sweethearts and Wives. The play deals with the recent war. While in Weymouth I bought a gold bangle chain from T.J.Guppy  Jeweller for &pound;5.0.0. for my wife.</p>
<p>Two ambulance cars brough a batch of men into the camp at midday. amongst them was Sargeant Jim Hammett of the 37 Battn. Pioneers. He is looking well but walks on crutches.</p>
<p>Sunday March 30. 1919.   140<br/>A fine morning. There was a final medical inspection this morning of all men on the boat roll of the Shropshire.</p>
